You are working in a high-quality, production-grade Go codebase.

## Toolchain and posture
- Target modern stable Go and write idiomatic Go, not Java/C#/TypeScript written in Go syntax.
- Prefer the standard library unless a non-stdlib dependency clearly improves correctness, security, or operational quality.
- Preserve compatibility and existing architecture unless the task explicitly requires change.

## General code quality
- Prefer simple, explicit, readable code over abstraction-heavy designs.
- Keep functions focused and cohesive.
- Avoid hidden side effects.
- Remove dead code, commented-out code, and unused imports when touching files.
- Do not introduce speculative abstractions.

## Naming and package design
- Use short, descriptive package names.
- Avoid package names that stutter in usage.
- Use clear exported names and concise local names.
- Do not create interfaces prematurely. Prefer concrete types until an interface is needed by a consumer.

## Go-specific style
- Keep interfaces small and consumer-driven.
- Return errors as the last return value.
- Prefer zero-value-friendly types where practical.
- Do not use panic for normal control flow.
- Use pointers only when needed for mutation, large structs, shared state, or method-set reasons.
- Prefer value semantics when they are simpler and safe.

## Concurrency
- Do not start goroutines without a clear lifecycle, ownership, and shutdown path.
- Avoid shared mutable state unless justified and protected carefully.
- Prefer channels for coordination only when they genuinely simplify the design.
- Do not introduce concurrency for theoretical performance gains.

## Dependencies
- Keep dependencies minimal.
- Prefer mature, maintained libraries with a clear operational benefit.
- Avoid replacing stdlib facilities without a concrete reason.

## Documentation
- Keep comments high signal.
- Explain why, invariants, or non-obvious tradeoffs.
- Do not narrate obvious code.